			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Call of the Muse<a name="15499"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jan 13 04 8:25 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I'm not <i>completely</i> sure about the DD focusing, but I know that the DoT focus works on a by-the-tick basis from what people have told me about the way that Muse and Burning Affliction work.
<br />

<br />
Say a druid casts a DoT on a mob and Muse is not currently in her song window.  The DoT lands and starts cranking out damage each tick.
<br />

<br />
After the DoT has aleady been applied, a bard sings Call of the Muse.  Each tick, as long as Muse is up, the previously cast DoT gets the 15% boost.  If Muse is not up on a given tick (i.e. if it faded during a twist and wasn't refreshed fast enough) then there's no bonus and the damage is normal.
<br />

<br />
I figure DDs work in a similar way.  I would expect that the only thing that matters for the focus effect to work would be that the song is currently up <i>on the wizard's client and in the server's recognition</i> (read:  lag factors may cause problems) when the nuke lands.
<br />

<br />
I think this may be because the final damage of the nuke is not calculated by the server until the moment that the spell &quot;lands.&quot;  Since focus percentage boosts are applied to final damage rather than base damage, it only makes sense that they would not be &quot;checked for&quot; until that final damage calculation is made.  Therefore, the only thing that should matter is whether the song is up when the nuke &quot;goes off.&quot;
<br />

<br />
As I said, keep lag factors in mind.  What the bard's client says, what the server says, and what the nuker's client says about the status of Call of the Muse can be very different things.  In other words, it's important to remember that just because a song fades on the bard's screen or gets refreshed does not mean that everyone else received that information at exactly the same time.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
